<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex</i> <i>hymenelytra</i> and/or <i>Tidestromia</i> <i>oblongifolia</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>confertifolia</i>, <i>Dalea</i> <i>mollissima</i>, <i>Encelia</i> <i>farinosa</i>, <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Peucephyllum</i> <i>schottii</i> and <i>Suaeda</i> <i>moquinii</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 1 m; canopy is open. Herbaceous layer is sparse to open with seasonal annuals. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Atriplex hymenelytra</i> > 1% absolute cover in the shrub canopy; no other species with equal or higher cover (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Atriplex hymenelytra</i> or <i>Tidestromia oblongifolia</i> > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Alluvial fans, washes, steep colluviums, rocky highlands, recent lava flows, cinder cones, heavy alkaline lake sediments, desert pavements. Soils develop from metamorphic, igneous, and sedimentary rocks that may be carbonate, alkaline, or salt rich.  </div>
</div>

        
