    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Cb). Stands are very local and occupy steep, colluvial slopes in alkaline badlands and mud hills west of the Salton Sea.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-o). <i>Atriplex hymenelytra</i> grows throughout the section, forming large stands hundreds of hectares in size on lower bajadas, rocky slopes, and alkaline mud hills in the Black Mountains (Schramm 1982), Cottonwood Mountains (Annable 1985) in Death Valley National Park, and generally in the central and eastern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Small stands occur locally on steep volcanic or alkaline slopes in the section, including the Cadiz-Vidal Valleys subsection (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Large stands occur on cinder fields, lava, and other volcanics. Those east of Owens Lake intermingle with <i>Suaeda moquinii</i> and <i>Atriplex confertifolia</i> alliances on wind-blown alkaline deposits on lower bajadas of the Inyo Mountains.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The alliance occurs in harsh environments rarely impacted by human-mediated disturbance, except by OHV activity in some areas (e.g., Trona Pinnacles). Management concerns are minimal except where grazing, mining, and OHV activity are present. As with other shrubby saltbushes, <i>Atriplex hymenelytra </i>is palatable to livestock. 

Thomas et al. (2004) suggested that <i>Tidestromia oblongifolia</i> becomes common in degraded <i>Atriplex confertifolia</i> and <i>Atriplex hymenelytra</i> stands in the Mojave Desert. However, it likely is just adapted to harsh, droughty conditions such as found on lower elevation desert bajadas. </div>
</div>

    

    

